, United Kingdom":"Rivington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Bradshaw, Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradshaw, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rivington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Rivington (Lancs). Medieval forms of this name are often indistinguishable from those for Rowington (Warwicks), but note Robertus Rivingtonman, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (Weeton, WR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Poll Tax","meanings":["1  Irish, Scottish Gaelic: relationship name: apparently a reduced form of an unrecorded Gaelic name,  <b>Mac Ruanaidh</b> ‘son of  <i>Ruanadh</i>’, a personal name from Gaelic  <i>ruanaidh</i> ‘strong man, champion’. The initial  <i>C</i> comes from the final consonant of  <i>mac</i>.  Compare  Rooney  .","2  English: of uncertain origin. It might be a variant of   Crowner   ‘coroner’, once a Sussex name, with the final syllable pronounced  <i>-ey</i>. Compare Simon Croner, 1296 in   Subsidy Rolls   (Horton, Tottington, and Edburton, Sussex); Willelmus Croner, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (South Mundham, Sussex). Alternatively it might be a variant of  <i>Corney</i> with the medial  <i>-r-</i> metathesized."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda de Rivington was born about 1165, in Rivington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert de Bradsea about 1172, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Bradshaw, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1165–":"umbes 1165–Surnud","1165–1189":"1165–1189","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","about 1182":"umbes 1172","1189":"1189","1165":"1165","about 1165":"umbes 1165","Abt 1182":"1182","1182":"1182","Rivington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Rivington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradshaw, Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradshaw, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1165–":"noin 1165–Kuollut","1165–1189":"1165–1189","1182–Male":"1182–Kuollut","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","about 1182":"noin 1172","1189":"1189","1165":"1165","about 1165":"noin 1165","Abt 1182":"1182","1182":"1182","Rivington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Rivington, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bradshaw, Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradshaw, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1165–":"environ 1165–Décédée","1165–1189":"1165–1189","1182–Male":"1182–Décédé","1165–Female":"1165–Décédée","about 1182":"environ 1172","1189":"1189","1165":"1165","about 1165":"environ 1165","Abt 1182":"1182","1182":"1182","Rivington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Rivington, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bradshaw, Bolton, Lancashire, E